{{afc comment|Wikidata entry [[d:Q11381863]] Wikidata name: Sumiyoshi-jinja [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 09:35, 11 June 2025 (UTC)}} {{Short description|Shinto shrine on Iki Island}} {{Infobox religious building | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | image = File:Sumiyoshi jinja (Iki) Haiden.JPG | caption = Honden | deity = [[Sumiyoshi sanjin]] | prefecture= {{ill|Iki|qid=Q861519}} | coordinates= {{Coord|33.788472222222225|N|129.70647222222223|E|region:JP_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | architecture_style= {{ill|nagare-zukuri|qid=Q210684}} }} '''Sumiyoshi Shrine (Iki City)''' is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located on [[Iki Island]] in [[:en:Japan|Japan]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Publishing |first=Bloomsbury |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pk7eEAAAQBAJ&dq=Sumiyoshi+shrine+Iki&pg=PA489 |title=Religious Celebrations [2 volumes]: An Encyclopedia of Holidays, Festivals, Solemn Observances, and Spiritual Commemorations [2 volumes] |date=2011-09-13 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing USA |isbn=978-1-59884-206-7 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Iki City Tourism Federation Website |url=http://shrine.ikikankou.com/english/meguri/ |access-date=2023-12-01 |website=Iki City Tourism Federation Website |language=ja}}</ref> It is a [[Beppyo Shrine]], or a shrine that is particularly notable in a certain way with a significant history to it.<ref>{{Cite web |title=別表神社とは？御朱印めぐりに参考になる「別表神社一覧」とマップ {{!}} 開運戦隊ゴシュインジャー |url=https://jinja-gosyuin.com/beppyou/ |access-date=2023-04-02 |website=jinja-gosyuin.com}}</ref>
In 927 it was listed as a [[:en:Myojin Taisha|Myojin Taisha]] in the [[Engishiki]].<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QmdRAAAAYAAJ&q=Sumiyoshi+Shrine+Iki+Island |title=Engi-shiki; Procedures of the Engi Era: Books VI-X |date=1972 |publisher=Sophia University |language=en}}</ref>
It is a branch shrine of [[Sumiyoshi-taisha]].<ref name="Japan-Today-2023a">{{Cite web |date=2023-04-20 |title=Japan's border islands of Tsushima and Iki offer simpler, slower pace of life |url=https://japantoday.com/Category/features/travel/Japan%E2%80%99s-border-islands-of-Tsushima-and-Iki-offer-simpler-slower-pace-of-life |access-date=2023-11-26 |website=Japan Today |language=en}}</ref> A shrine located in Osaka.<ref>Breen, John ''et al.'' (2000). [https://books.google.com/books?id=MADlfH002mAC&q=oharano ''Shinto in History: Ways of the Kami,'' pp. 74-75.]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120213073802/http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/images/uploads/EOS070712Ab.pdf "Nationwide List of ''Ichinomiya''," p. 3.]; retrieved 2011-08-09</ref><ref>Ponsonby-Fane, Richard. (1959). ''The Imperial House of Japan,'' pp. 125.</ref>
It is one of the oldest Sumiyoshi shrines alongside ''[[Sumiyoshi Shrine (Fukuoka)|Sumiyoshi jinja]]'' in [[:en:Hakata-ku, Fukuoka|Hakata-ku]], [[:en:Fukuoka, Fukuoka|Fukuoka]] city, [[:en:Fukuoka Prefecture|Fukuoka Prefecture]], and [[:en:Moto Sumiyoshi Shrine|Moto Sumiyoshi Shrine]] in [[:en:Kobe|Kobe]], [[:en:Hyōgo Prefecture|Hyōgo Prefecture]]. However, it is not known which one of these is the oldest.<ref>Nussbaum, Louis-Frédéric and Käthe Roth. (2005). [https://books.google.com/books?id=p2QnPijAEmEC ''Japan encyclopedia.''] Cambridge: [[:en:Harvard University Press|Harvard University Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-674-01753-5}}; [http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/58053128?referer=di&ht=edition OCLC 58053128]</ref>
Strangely for a sea god shrine, it is located in the center of the Island. The shrine has a myth that it is located in the center because the gods were disturbed by the sound of the waves.<ref name="Japan-Today-2023a" />
